      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "1. Overview"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "The stored procedure "
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "ManualBilling_RetrieveBillingPeriodRevisionAndFirstBillingCancelled",
          "marks": [
            {
              "type": "code"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " is designed to retrieve specific billing periods for a given account within a specified date range. It identifies the billing period revision and the first billing period that was effectively canceled based on certain criteria. The procedure operates within the context of manual billing processes, likely for utility companies, and uses information from the "
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Billing.Account",
          "marks": [
            {
              "type": "code"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " and "
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "ManualBill.ReadingScheduleManualBilling",
          "marks": [
            {
              "type": "code"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": " tables."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "attrs": {
        "level": 1
      },
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "2. Complexity Level: Medium"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "The procedure involves multiple SQL operations, including joins, conditional logic, and the use of Common Table Expressions (CTEs). It also incorporates user-defined functions to calculate billing days, which adds to its complexity. The logic is straightforward but requires a good understanding of the underlying data model and business rules."
        }
